Question 1: List the name of airlines where the destination is MIA airport with their average arrival delays and sort them from the smallest to largest average arrival delays. Use data frames flights and airlines.

We shall solve this question using R, SQL, and Python.

R solution

You can use the R command inner_join() to join two tables.

# Code here
df = inner_join(flights, airlines, by = "carrier")
library(dplyr)



drr = df %>% 
  filter(dest %in% c("MIA")) %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% 
  summarise(mean.delay=mean(arr_delay,na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(mean.delay)
drr
# A tibble: 3 Ã 2
  name                   mean.delay
  <chr>                       <dbl>
1 American Airlines Inc.      -1.88
2 Delta Air Lines Inc.         2.27
3 United Air Lines Inc.        6.66

SQL solution

Write your SQL query in the function sqldf(). For example,sqldf("select * from relig_income") list all rows in the data frame relig_income.

# Example
#sqldf("select * from relig_income limit 3")
# code here
dfsql=sqldf("select name as 'airline name', AVG(arr_delay) as 'average arrival delays' from df WHERE
    dest  = 'MIA'
  GROUP BY
    name
  ORDER BY
    'average arrival delays'")

dfsql

2   Delta Air Lines Inc.               2.268091

Python solution

Use pd.join() from pandas. You can either import data from the R package into Python or use the data Python package nycflights13

# load python libraries 
import pandas as pd
# load data
import statsmodels.api as stat
dp = stat.datasets.get_rdataset("airlines", "nycflights13").data
da = stat.datasets.get_rdataset("flights", "nycflights13").data
airlines = pd.DataFrame(dp)
flights = pd.DataFrame(da)


# code here
af = airlines.set_index('carrier').join(flights.set_index('carrier'))

mia = ['MIA']
df_mia = af[af['dest'].isin(mia)]

avg_delay = df_mia.groupby('name')['arr_delay'].mean().reset_index()
sort = avg_delay.sort_values(by='arr_delay')
sort
                     name  arr_delay
0  American Airlines Inc.  -1.878482
1    Delta Air Lines Inc.   2.268091
2   United Air Lines Inc.   6.655685

Question 2: Plot the boxplot of the departure delays vs the name of airlines where the destination is MIA airport. Solve this question using R and Python.

R solution

Use ggplot

# code here
library(ggplot2)

rr = df %>% 
  filter(dest %in% c("MIA"))

ggplot(rr,aes(x=name,y=dep_delay)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "blue", color = "black")+
  labs(title = "Boxplot of Departure Delays for MIA Flights by Airline",
       x = "Airline Name",
       y = "Departure Delay (minutes)")

Python solution

You can use pandas.boxplot() or seaborn.boxplot(). You can either import data from the R package into Python or use the data Python package nycflights13

# import python libraries
import pandas as pd 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib

# data
af = airlines.set_index('carrier').join(flights.set_index('carrier'))

mia = ['MIA']
df_mia = af[af['dest'].isin(mia)]

# Boxplot
plt.figure()
df_mia.boxplot(column='dep_delay', by='name')
plt.title('Boxplot of Departure Delays for MIA Flights by Airline')
plt.xlabel('Airline Name')
plt.ylabel('Departure Delay (minutes)')
plt.show()

Question 3: For each airlines, 1) find the month where the average departure delay time is the highest in the year. 2) Make a visualization to show the results. Solve this question using your preferred language R or Python.

# Do not forget to specify which language you will use
#I am using R 
# load libraries 
library(nycflights13)
library(sqldf)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

# load data
dff = inner_join(flights, airlines, by = "carrier")


dff2 = dff %>% 
  group_by(name, month) %>% 
  summarise(mean.delay=mean(dep_delay,na.rm = TRUE)) 

# 1) code here to find the months
max_delay_month = dff2 %>% 
  group_by(name) %>%
  filter(mean.delay==max(mean.delay)) %>% 
  arrange(mean.delay)
